# Manual /soul-heartbeat command, independent of the automatic scheduler

Status: accepted — implementation pending (2026-07-13)

## Context
HEARTBEAT.md grounding currently fires only on the automatic turn_end schedule (ADR-0001).
Users want to re-ground the active Soul on demand, not wait for the next scheduled beat.

## Decision
Add an extension command `soul-heartbeat` (the soul-* command family) that injects the ACTIVE
Soul's heartbeatContent on demand, reusing the scheduler's exact LLM-facing payload: customType
"soul-heartbeat-reminder", display:false, wrapped in <soul-heartbeat-reminder type="grounding"
no-response> … </soul-heartbeat-reminder>. It also emits a notifyUI confirmation so the hidden
injection is observable.

It is PURELY ADDITIVE: it neither reads nor resets the scheduler's activation-anchored count.
That count stays lexically private to registerHeartbeatReminderHandler (the isolation ADR-0001
established). Manual grounding and the automatic cadence are orthogonal.

It IGNORES heartbeatMode entirely. off | lite | full | N govern only the AUTOMATIC cadence; an
explicit manual invocation overrides that — a manual /soul-heartbeat fires even when the mode is
"off". Gated only by: an active Soul, level >= 3, and heartbeatContent present — each refusal
surfaced via notifyUI, never a silent no-op.

## Considered options
- Reset the auto-cadence on manual fire (rejected): needs a shared handle into the scheduler
  closure, re-introducing the cross-module coupling ADR-0001 removed; manual grounding is orthogonal
  to the automatic cadence.
- Suppress the manual fire when heartbeatMode === "off" (rejected): surprising — the user asked for
  it by hand; "off" disables automatic firing, not the existence of content to send.
- Pi-native prompt path (promptPaths) instead of an extension command (rejected): static, resolved
  at session start from directories, cannot track "the active Soul" at invocation time.

## Consequences
- Manual and automatic heartbeats share ONE LLM-facing payload shape — no second grounding format.
- A manual fire one turn before an automatic one double-grounds; harmless (same content; grounding
  is not damaged by repetition).
- "Heartbeat mode" narrows in the glossary to "governs the automatic cadence only".
